            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Avi Popov\u2019s San Francisco story began not in a Marina high-rise but in the foggy, close-knit Inner Richmond district. The only child of Russian Jewish immigrants who arrived in the early 90s, he grew up in a world of Cyrillic newspapers and the scent of rye bread from a local bakery. His parents worked grueling, low-wage jobs, and their exhaustion permeated their small, rent-controlled apartment. High school felt abstract and disconnected from the immediate need to contribute. At 17, Avi dropped out to work full-time\u2014first at a deli, then as a delivery driver\u2014bringing a much-needed second income to the family. He earned his GED a few years later, a pragmatic act of self-improvement.\n\nThe turning point came not in a classroom, but in a sterile hospital waiting room. While helping his mother navigate a confusing medical diagnosis, tangled in insurance paperwork and language barriers, Avi discovered a hidden talent: he was a natural advocate. He was patient, methodical, and possessed an unshakeable calm that reassured his terrified mother. This experience was a revelation. He found an entry-level position at a local non-profit and, through sheer competence and empathy, worked his way up to Patient Navigator.\n\nNow 37, Avi is a human compass for the city\u2019s most vulnerable. His days are spent on the phone, in clinics, and in community centers, helping new immigrants, the elderly, and low-income families untangle the bureaucracies of healthcare and social services. His daily 4.5-mile commute on the rattling 38-Geary bus is a time for quiet reflection, mentally preparing for the human challenges ahead.\n\nAvi lives in the same Richmond neighborhood he grew up in, now in his own small one-bedroom. His social life is a tight circle of childhood friends, most of whom share a similar working-class background. His hopes are not grand; he dreams of one day affording a condo in his neighborhood and getting a specialized certification to better serve his clients. He feels a fierce, protective love for a San Francisco that exists beyond the tech headlines\u2014a city of resilience, community, and quiet dignity, a city he helps hold together, one patient at a time."
